        <h2>Basics of Meal Prepping</h2>
        <br />
        <p>
            Once you have purchased your food storage, here are the next steps:

            <ol>
                <li>
                    You should calculate the calories you need to lose weight. You can do so here:<a href="https://www.niddk.nih.gov/bwp" target="_blank">Body Weight Planner</a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    And if you want to do some research, read<a href="https://www.trifectanutrition.com/blog/best-weight-loss-foods" target="_blank">this</a>
                    for the best foods on weight loss.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>

            Next,<strong>Start Small</strong>. When I first began Meal tracking, I only made 1 Meal for lunches for Monday-Friday. As you get better, you can
            add on Breakfast prep and eventually dinner.

            Rembember,<strong>Sensible Portions</strong>. Portion control is key to weight loss, but it's also the key to a "healthier you". I would suggest buying a
            <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Etekcity-Digital-Kitchen-Multifunction-Removable/dp/B07JB2XRNT" target="_blank">Food Scale</a>
            <strong>AND Using this AMAZING MEAL TRACKER!</strong>

            Also, if you think you may not remember to add foods to your list or track your foods, keep a daily reminder on your phone. I for one have A LOT of daily reminders added to my phone.
            I have a tendency to forget. With the hustle and bustle of daily life, being a personal chauffer to your children, work, trying to remember to get your cardio in, remembering to breathe etc..
            daily reminders take one less stresser out of life.

        </p>
